{
  "text": "The widespread existence of a structurally homozygous bisexual diploid form of St. diplomutata often co-occurring with the highly polymorphic parthenogenetic triploid form, might suggest a multiple and allopolyploid origin of the triploid; in this case, the homozygous bisexual diploid would contribute the standard sequences for all chromosome arms and the various inverted sequences would have to have been contributed by a closely related hypothetical diploid apomict (i.e., a diploid parthenogenetic form). Although it would not be easy to detect facultative diploid apomicts, such a situation is highly unlikely [CITATION_1] since it is hard to envision a diploid apomict crossing with a bisexual diploid to form a viable triploid automict.",
